</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/urittdabard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>rittdabard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/14/02 9:33:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3107.topic&index=86>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Economics for today</span><hr size=1> First off let's get the inconsequential out of the way.Yes Will Shakespeare owned and/or invested in several businesses, but was ultimately a failure as a businessman, because he would inevitably, to our benefit, be drawn back to his writing and plays, thus ignore his business duties. Even Will understood this, thus he entrusted the running of The Globe to others. <br>
<br>
Now as for your mention of Wonder, You say they would go out of business if they didn't have investors. You say that that investment capital is what pays their workers wages, and you said <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> I</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> didn't understand corporations. Well, let's face facts Wonders bread is buttered (figuratively) by bread(literally). Investment capital is almost invariable used for capturing greater shares of the consumer market, via advertising, product placement, promotionals and/or buying of competition. When they gain more of the market, in this case baked goods, profits increase. This does not necessarily create jobs, in fact when smaller companies are absorbed it often eliminates jobs, because it is often cheaper to close down a plant than to retool it to your brands specifications. <br>
<br>
Now since you want only to read that is an argument for taxing rich vs taxing generally and completely ignore the times I point out that it is basically a type of insurance the government takes out on the environment in which those most cost them the money for clean ups are the ones who foot the lion's share of the bill. When one looks at it from that perspective, however, it becomes quite obvious that your &quot;tax the rich and they can't employ&quot; argument is Trickledown Economics. Anyone with foresight or a knowledge of eighties economics knows that Trickledown, Supplyside, or Reaganomics as it is also known does not work in practice. It is truly a utopian concept, but like its counterpoint, communism, it works only on paper. As soon as you throw in the human element into the equation the system breaks down quicker than Ronnie's bowels after his daily BAP treatment.You see any extra money ending up at the top is hardly noticed and will have minimal affect on spending habits in the economy. You give a hundred thousand dollar tax break to Bill Gates or one of the Walton kids and it isn't going to change their daily expenditures. Now take that same one thousand dollars and divide it up amongst one thousand members of the lower and middle class and the majority of it will be pumped back into the economy within a few months. That equates to more bread sold. That is what truly pays the wages of workers at Wonder. I know you want to tell me that similarly that money could have been invested in Wonder, however that will does not increase thier production, so they use it to capture a greater share of the market. Once that money is spent capturing a greater share of a market not growing because of &quot;lack of consumer confidence&quot; (read: penny pinching) there is truly no actual growth. By figuring in the money of investors it leads to a bloating of figures that companies are pressured to reach. When production slows to meet the diminished demands the CEOs who bear the brunt of responsibility are called on to &quot;trim the fat&quot;. Is it ever the true fat that gets trimmed, like corporate salaries and fringe, or the ad budget, or is it more likely to be lay-offs and closings. I think one walk through Flint will answer that. You see ultimately what determines if a company makes it or not is production. Ask all those folks smarter than me that sank their dough in them thar boomin' dotcoms. So yes it is my belief that the rich bearing a perportionate share of the tax burden is the best way to run the system because dividing the taxes evenly where each person pays x% eats up a grater percentage of the poorer classes incomes, thus taking a large portion (90% control only 10% remember) of the demand out of a system built on supply and demand and causing the system to bottom out. So I guess what I am saying is the idea that tax breaks for the rich creates jobs holds about as much ground as the French Resistance.<br>
<br>
Let's face it the talking heads no more about this than us. Do you think there is a reason that nobody post-Reagan mentions supplyside economics, even though Bush Sr., Clinton, Dole, Gore, Bush Jr., hell even Ross Perot, included pieces of it in thier agendas? It is because they spend fortunes on assessing public opinion and the public bristles at the those terms, so the find new more friendly terminology for their plans. Your assessment that the majority of the people not caring  is also a proven fact, because of Bushie's withdrawal from the Kyoto accords that every other civilizied nation has signed, many of the other nations are holding us to standards of unfair business practices, since our companies have lower standards than the rest of the world. This will allow them to place tariffs on our goods. So it is only short-sighted jingoist morons, and those extremely disinfranchised by the sytem where the very lobbyist you cheer on have rendered their words meaningless to their representatives that don't give a crap. The rest of the world certainly does. <br>
<br>
I want to say I do agree with you on the point you don't seem to agree with yourself on...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u> You haven't come up with anything yet that Bush has done that I disagree with.<br>
<br>
I do disagree with Bush on one aspect, that of oil drilling. <br>
<br>
