<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Yep, if people are allowed to profit and we don't redistribute wealth through taxation eventually a couple of people will have it all and everyone else will starve because nobody can start a new business and there are no jobs<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not true at all. Even before taxation, wealth is distributed. Someone will need to work the &quot;low paying jobs&quot;. Take a look at the Gini Coefficient before income taxation and after, it isn't all that much changes (Gini coefficient = measure on inequality in an economy).<br>
<br>
In fact, the reason it doesn't change &quot;that much&quot; is because income taxation is one of the few forms of progressive taxation. Most other taxes are &quot;head/poll&quot; taxes, and therefore, &quot;regressive&quot; in a sense. A 15% tak on a loaf  of bread for someone making $10,000 a year is a lot more then someone making $1000,00 a year.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The economy is a finite pie <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The economy is not a finite pie, it's growth in infinite over the long run. Through innovation and productivity growth, theoritically, economic growth is infinite.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There is obviously a limit to the number of bread companies that can be supported by a finite population of bread consumers<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Right. But because there are a finite number of consumers, that DOES NOT mean that the opportunity for economic growth is also finite. You could, instead, improve the quality of the bread and charge $1 more for the bread, resulting in economic growth. This type of growth is infinite. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  one expands another must diversify or keep up or die, that is the competitive nature of capitalism, which is good.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Of course, one of my favourite economists, Schumpeter famous theory of &quot;creative destruction&quot;, which simply states that in the long run, if you are to survive, you must change and adapt to be competitive. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> However when we start rewarding those already at the top there is no room for new companies to enter a saturated market<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't think that's true. Look at car companies, one of North America's most prominent Oligopolies. Ford/GM/Chrystler dominate the market share, yet brand new car companies are able to start up and be successful (Saturn/Kia anyone?)<br>
<br>
You can reward &quot;top&quot; companies, however, you need to make sure they run there companies in a competive and free market system - not as as monopoly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uarrhenius1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arrhenius1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/15/02 9:48:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3107.topic&index=92>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Economics for today</span><hr size=1> Bravo, Cenelron!  That was an outstanding post, and I couldn't agree more.  I'm a conservative, just like you, and guess what...I'm not exactly what you would call &quot;whitey.&quot;  In fact, I'm quite brown! *gasp*<br>
