whiner were in your posts.  And you used them like 6 times. Can you put aside your liberal<br>
propaganda manual for a minute or two and actually respond to what is said?<br>
<br>
&lt;insert general statement here about how the 2001 recession was the result of Clinton’s<br>
economic policies&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;insert general statement here about how the 1981 recession was the result of Carter’s economic<br>
policies&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;insert general conclusion here about how liberals don’t know the first thing about the economy<br>
since there were recessions at the conclusion of democratic administrations&gt;<br>
<br>
I can play the broad generalities game too. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
No, you shouldn’t get the majority say.  This is a Republic, not a Democracy.  Whether it is<br>
politically correct to state it or not, the truth is that our government is specifically designed to put<br>
more educated, responsible and SUCCESSFUL/ACCOMPLISHED/CAPABLE people in control<br>
of the decision making in order to keep “mass” rule from taking place.  If it were a true<br>
democracy then every couple of years 51% of the voters could get together and say that everyone<br>
who has more money than them should have their money confiscated and given to the<br>
51%....kind of where you head where your argument and where some Democrats would already<br>
have us if they could get away with it.  <br>
<br>
<br>
And your “employer or clients telling the you how to spend your check” example is, yet again,<br>
another completely baseless example.  Do you not see what an absolute foolish statement<br>
(although it does reflect typical liberal thinking) that is?  I EARN the money in my check from<br>
my clients or employer.  You do not EARN the money taken by the government and the<br>
government doesn’t EARN the money.  I should have control over the spending of money that I<br>
EARN.  This whole working for your money concept is really just beyond your capacity, isn’t it?  <br>
<br>
And this is a good time to point out your statement:<br>
<br>
“Unfortunately we (the bleeding hearts) can't bring up any issue involving money and the<br>
government without someone trying to pin the blame on welfare. I simply cannot believe people<br>
think that $415 of which less than $50 is probably abused is such a drain on the economy. They<br>
glance right over the $1388 per person that goes to corporations and stare at the $415. That $415<br>
includes school programs and help for the handicapped, the $1388 includes helping McDonald's<br>
promote McNuggets overseas, but does not include the tax credits Exxon gets for cleaning up<br>
their mess in Prince William Sound.”<br>
<br>
<br>
How can the difference here escape you? #1 - the $415 goes to millions of people, not a few<br>
thousand corporations and #2 YOU ARE COMPARING GIVING MONEY AWAY TO<br>
PEOPLE WHO DID NOT EARN IT TO SIMPLY NOT TAKING AWAY AS MUCH OF<br>
SOMEONE ELSE’S MONEY!!!!!  The corporations earn money and pay taxes and are given<br>
REDUCTIONS in the taxes that are forcibly taken away from them. “Corporate welfare” is not<br>
welfare, it is a reduction in corporate raping by taxation.  It is really very simple.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
What horrible record on minorities does Bush have?  That he doesn’t believe in giving them<br>
preferential treatment and discriminating against others in favor of them?  But yeah, I can see<br>
how your willingness to point out a perceived flaw in someone you hate anyway because he is<br>
not a liberal is real proof of your true concern of others.  That was sarcasm if you couldn’t tell<br>
from my tone. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Again, you are the only one who has used the words lazy-whiner as near as I can tell, although I<br>
would certainly say that I would and could use those words to describe some people.  And maybe<br>
I did say that earlier, but I can’t find it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<br>
I have no clue what you are trying to say in the devaluation paragraph and it appears that you<br>
have no clue either.  It sounds like you are making an argument against limitless printing of<br>
money because it will devalue the money and ruin the economy....&lt;shrug&gt; don’t know where that<br>
is coming from.<br>
<br>
<br>
Heh, good theory, take away the corporations money because they are a threat and then give<br>
some back to them if they prove that they behave how you want them to.....freedom at it’s best. <br>
Thanks, comrade, but I will pass on that type of society.<br>
<br>
<br>
“Hard work is it’s own reward” is a good moral theory but a terrible economic theory.  When will<br>
liberals quit trying to force their morality on everyone else?  Soon as you point out one<br>
conservative who has said that everyone who is not financially well to do are not successful or<br>
hard working then you will get one small bit of credibility.  You obviously have ABSOLUTELY<br>
NO CLUE what conservatives believe because you cannot even read written posts and respond<br>
without imagining slanders and biases.<br>
<br>
<br>
Here’s another chance for you:  The sky outside is blue.<br>
<br>
Will Ritt’s next post say “Those damn conservatives all believe the sky is green and that it is<br>
caused by not murdering enough minorities each day...?”<br>
<br>
Stay tuned....<br>
