Your artist law is a perfect example of your obvious inability to comprehend the tax system. If an artist is in a 50% tax bracket basically he is creating one work for the government the next for himself.  Stephen King talked about this in the beginning of a collection of his short stories. Someone pointed out to him how he was virtually losing money because when he wrote short stories, but he said they were things he felt like doing so he did. The government doesn't tell the CEOs how much they are going to need and then let them decide how they are going to make that much. It taxes them, just as the artist by how much they make. Even these superfund taxes, when you look at them actually, are like that. The governement takes into account several things like income and potential environmental risks.  I never said anyone should pay my share of taxes. Explain to me how the cleanup of  a chemical used in a product that might not even be sold in my country/state/county is rightfully my share that I am trying to dodge. NOW EXPLAIN TO ME IS IT EASIER TO GIVE TAX BREAKS TO ENVIRONMENTALLY FRIENDLY COUNTRIES OR ENVIRONMENTALLY FRIENDLY INDIVIDUALS. <br>
